      {
        "id": 3266390,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2021-11-04T05:05:19.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"3\" data-topic=\"174535\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>Alan, please take this question in the spirit I\u2019m asking. I\u2019m pretty new to champagne, and, as I mentioned in the main champagne thread, I pay very close attention to tasting notes because enthusiasm and/or high scores won\u2019t necessarily steer me on the right path.</p>\n<p>When I read your note, it sounds very different from what William Kelley described in his note, other than the interplay of apple and citrus (he says pear, but similar enough). You say \u201clean and linear,\u201d whereas he says \u201cFull-bodied, vinous and layered, it\u2019s deep and concentrated, framed by racy acids and chalky structuring dry extract. It\u2019s a serious, muscular Champagne that\u2019s long and intense.\u201d \u201cFull-bodied,\u201d \u201cdeep\u201d and \u201cmuscular\u201d sounds to me different from \u201clean and linear.\u201d Do you think that what you tasted is different from what William described, or are you emphasizing an aspect that stood out particularly for you, such as the \u201cracy acids\u201d?</p>\n<p>Incidentally, your description sounds closer to how Stephan Reinhardt described the 2012 version: \u201cOn the palate, this is a lovely pure, crisp and graceful Champagne with a very charming style of minerality. It is lean but vital, very mineral and almost steely but combined with ripe yet refreshing citrus fruit and lingering complexity.\u201d</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Not Alan, but rather a response from my side: you\u2019re quite right to pay attention to the notes because there\u2019s such stylistic diversity in contemporary Champagne! This particular wine comes from a small walled vineyard behind the Doyard estate in Vertus, planted with 60-year-old vines that are cordon-pruned (which makes for smaller berries and lower total yields too). It\u2019s picked ripe, and vinified in oak. So I would say it is unavoidably quite a concentrated, muscular, vinous Champagne. But, it is also quite structured, sees minimal dosage (2.4 g for the disgorgement of 2014 that I tasted), is produced from just the core of the coeur du cuv\u00e9e (the lowest pH juice), and was disgorged recently (2020); so it\u2019s a wine that\u2019s quite tightly wound out of the gates. Right now, I think it\u2019s as the wine warms in the glass and gets a bit closer to room temperature that all its texture and concentration become most apparent.</p>",
